@@dShadowmere, the Blighted Crownlands@@N

  Not merely a haunted fortress. Shadowmere is the ruin of a @@ystate
project@@N: a frontier march founded to extend Midgaard's law, logistics,
and burial order into unstable territory. Its horror comes from policy
choices that outlived their emergency context.

  The Crown sponsored a fortified march-town at the crossroads of
military roads, farm belts, and burial tracts. Its mandate: guard
transit, tax goods, process war dead and plague dead before they
reached core city districts, and keep records admissible in Midgaard
tribunals. From its beginning, Shadowmere mixed sword and ledger.

  When blight-fevers and battlefield contagions spread, Midgaard issued
the @@rPlague Mandate@@N: rapid intake, forced quarantines, immediate
cremation powers, and temporary suspension of lineage appeals.
@@rTemporary became permanent.@@N Shadowmere built trenches, processing
halls, poison works, and deep binding cells. What had been a frontier
court became an intake machine for the dead and near-dead.

  After plague peaks receded, no authority agreed on rollback. Crown
envoys demanded restored precedence. Compact wardens insisted
containment powers remain. Temple delegates sought release rites.
March commanders refused to relinquish emergency chains. The @@rLast
Bell Crisis@@N saw three contradictory decrees rung in one night --
amnesty, lockdown, and requisition. Garrisons split. The city did
not fall in one battle; it calcified into mutually hostile systems.

  The @@eBlight Hydrology Doctrine@@N tells Shadowmere's environmental
story. Original runoff channels were tied to burial and quarantine
districts. During crisis years, alchemical waste, blood sacrifice
residues, and preservative salts entered the same waterways. Sealed
crypts flooded from below. Low fields became permanent toxic wetlands.
The blight is not accidental corruption -- it is infrastructure memory.

  Five factions claim legitimacy. The @@eOathbound March@@N patrols walls
with rigid discipline, executing chain-of-command instructions from a
government that no longer exists. The @@rCrimson Household@@N occupies
former compounds under bloodline continuity of estate charters. The
@@dBinder Collegium@@N treats souls as entries requiring categorization.
The @@dGallows Syndicate@@N turned execution infrastructure into an
economy of venom and coercion. And in the blackwater channels, fen-
adapted remnants prove ecological succession beyond governance.

  For Midgaard scholars, Shadowmere is proof that @@ylawful systems
become predatory when emergency powers lose their limits@@N.
